<!--
VOICING PLAN:
- Key: G major (1 sharp, F#). Standard hymn harmonization: I–IV–V–I with D7 passing chords.
- Bars 1-8 (A section, repeated): 2-note RH with half-note harmonic rhythm,
  4-note LH open voicings. Variety achieved by using 1st inversion G at bar 5.
- Bar 9 (B section): 3-note RH begins, RH at G4-B4-D5 = G root position triad.
- Bar 10: Suspension in RH (A4 sustained through D→G change, then resolves to B4).
  Creates a classic 4-3 suspension on the dominant.
- Bar 11: Climax — full 3-note RH with C, D7, G in quick succession at quarter-note rate.
- Bar 12: Final G root position cadence with all hands full.

VOICE LEADING HIGHLIGHTS:
- Bar 2: RH inner voice E4→F#4→G4 echoes the bass stepwise approach to G.
  LH C2→D2→G2 provides strong bass line descending a 5th.
- Bar 10: RH A4 suspension (4th over D bass) resolves to B4 when G arrives — textbook
  4-3 suspension. This is the most interesting moment of voice leading.
- Bar 11: RH expands to full triads for the first time, building to full 3-stave texture.
- Bars 1 vs 5: Same melody, different LH bass: G2 root (bar 1) → B2 first inversion (bar 5)
  for bass line variety on the repetition.

TEXTURE ARC:
- Bars 1-8: Consistent 2-note RH + 4-note LH. Clear and hymn-like.
- Bar 9: 3-note RH enters with ascending inner voice figure.
- Bar 10: Suspension creates tension at the high point.
- Bars 11-12: Full 3-note RH throughout climax and cadence. Widest span.
-->
